reviews.author: Renzo Patricio Carpio
reviews.text:
Great experience seeing animals that are native to Peru, especially the ones in the Sierra and Selva: condors, vicunas, alpacas, variety of monkeys (including the smallest one in South America), otorongos (jaguars), other different large felines, ronsocos (capybaras), etc.
Recommend coming during weekdays when it is not as busy so you can snap better pictures of your favorite animals.

reviews.author: Robert Sigman
reviews.text: I was amazed.  I've been to several US zoos.  This one blows them away.  As an added bonus, they built the zoo around 500-2000 year old Huaca ruins.

reviews.text:
Very pretty and underrated, you must be well organized when you visit the park of legends, if you want to see everything, if you go through a specific area, etc.
The mountains are generally where I start and although many things improved due to the pandemic, the mountains did not need major repairs because it was always the best maintained area, whether the roads and walls are made of stone, I don't know how the mine is still the same. The only thing I would make a small change to is the staff that works at the mine, so rude.
It has some nice cassettes to take photos (entering through the waterfall, you continue straight ahead and at the first entrance to the right, right in the first hallway to your right they are there again on the stone wall).
There is a souvenir shop, the viewpoint which is very nice now that it is cleaner and more tidy.

reviews.author: Louis Cecile
reviews.text: This large zoo provides family fun with plenty of zoned areas to discover. The ticket gates can be quite chaotic to navigate, but it is recommended to keep moving to find a less busy queue. Your belief system will dictate whether you wish to visit a zoo and may see some animals that seem stressed in their environment. There are various zones of types of animals to explore and the zoo is vast to discover. There are plenty of refreshment points and shops scattered around the zoo. The seal and monkey areas are particularly exciting for their playful natures. Overall it provides a good family experience that is hard to see in one day.

reviews.author: Sonja Mitterlehner
reviews.text:
This park is an oasis for both humans and animals. Many people come to the park to relax, bringing blankets and food from the market stalls (right outside the entrance). Family-friendly and wheelchair accessible, there are food stalls and restaurants at reasonable prices.

Don't forget sunscreen and a hat. Regular sneakers are sufficient.

Highly recommended :-)

reviews.text: One of my favorite areas of the immense park of legends, it has animals from all over the world, although they are not many, there are enough to appreciate the majestic nature, you can see the heavy hippos, the no less heavy buffalo, the giraffe showing off its immense size, the zebras grazing, felines such as: tigers, there is also the Bengal tiger, you can also see the king of the jungle, the "Lion", you will also find a camel, ostriches and other animals. Highly recommended!

reviews.author: Anne Marieke van der Wal
reviews.text: Considering the size of Lima there is remarkably little to do for kids. This park is one of the few fun things. It's quite small. You're done in two hours. But it's a fun distraction for kids aged below 10 years old.

reviews.author: Ludvina
reviews.text: Pretty fun experience for kids, my 6 year old enjoyed himself for about 3 hours here. There is an aquarium, some tunnels with dinosaur animatronics, an Africa themed train ride , an earthquake simulator... Additionally, they have some paid rides and jumpy games not included in the 15 soles entrance. It is no Disney world, but it's something to do with kids in Lima.

reviews.author: Jesus Angulo
reviews.text:
2022 marks the year of the park's takeoff, as it looks completely renovated. In addition to the original attractions‚Äîthe little train, the motorboat, the Jungle area, the Coast, and the aquarium‚Äîa series of inflatable games have been added, the most notable being the Island in the Lagoon, the New Jungle, a new inflatable that allows for family fun.
What has improved significantly are the restaurants and the food offerings on the go. There is a wide variety of cuisine, ranging from traditional grilled chicken, regional dishes, and fast food stands and restaurants in the country-style Felinario area.
The renovated 5D cinema is operational, but it is actually a 3D cinema with some additional effects, water, and compressed air.

reviews.author: Rita Sato
reviews.text:
15 soles for admission, and there's also a charge for parking.
The zoo is super complete, with every animal you can imagine. The park is super clean.
The boat ride is paid separately, 10 soles for a wristband. It goes through a tunnel with a miniature Machu Picchu.
I always went on a family outing. You can bring in food and drinks, and there's space for picnic tables and chairs. Bring water inside‚Äîwater is gold.
I love Leyenda Park, San Miguel, Lima.
